\pard\qc\f0\b\fs36 Auphonic 403 Failure Analysis\b0\fs24\par
\pard\qc\fs20\cf5 MattrMindrScribe Production Server -- March 18, 2026\par
UPDATED: Second investigation after initial fixes failed\cf1\par
\pard\par

\pard\f0\b\fs28 1. THE ERROR\b0\fs24\par
\par
The EC2 production server consistently returns this error when attempting to process audio through the Auphonic pipeline:\par
\par
\pard\li720\f1\fs20\cf2 Auphonic create production failed (403): \{\par
  "status_code": 403,\par
  "error_code": null,\par
  "error_message": "Token doesn\rquote t exist",\par
  "form_errors": \{\},\par
  "data": null\par
\}\cf1\f0\fs24\par
\pard\par
The error occurs at the very first API call -- creating a new production via POST to /api/productions.json. The 403 with "Token doesn\rquote t exist" means Auphonic\rquote s API received the request but rejected the authentication token.\par
\par
The same Auphonic API key works perfectly from the Replit development environment (confirmed: account benw52592, 21 credits). The failure is isolated to the EC2 production server.\par
\par

\pard\f0\b\fs28 2. WHAT HAS BEEN TRIED AND RULED OUT\b0\fs24\par
\par
\pard\li360\b Attempt 1: Changed "bearer" (lowercase) to "Basic" auth\b0\par
\pard\li720 Hypothesis was that Auphonic required HTTP Basic Auth (apikey: as username, empty password). Testing confirmed this was wrong -- Bearer token auth is the correct method. Basic Auth returned different errors.\par
\par
\pard\li360\b Attempt 2: Changed "bearer" (lowercase) to "Bearer" (capitalized)\b0\par
\pard\li720 Testing from Replit confirmed that "Bearer" (capital B) works for the /api/user.json endpoint (returned 200 with account details). However, the EC2 server still returned 403 after this change. This rules out case-sensitivity of the auth scheme as the sole cause.\par
\par
\pard\li360\b Attempt 3: Fixed wrong API key on EC2\b0\par
\pard\li720 The initial deployment accidentally set an Anthropic API key (sk-ant-api03-...) as the AUPHONIC_API_KEY. This was identified and corrected -- the .env file was edited to contain only the correct 32-character Auphonic key. The duplicate "your_key_here" placeholder entry was also removed. Despite this correction, the 403 persists.\par
\par
\pard\li360\b Attempt 4: Updated algorithm settings and polling logic\b0\par
\pard\li720 The algorithm configuration was updated to match Auphonic\rquote s reference documentation (speech_isolation, denoiseamount: 100, etc.) and the polling status codes were corrected. These changes are unrelated to the 403 auth error since the failure occurs before any audio processing begins.\par
\pard\par

\pard\f0\b\fs28 3. MOST LIKELY CAUSE: dotenv IS NOT LOADING THE .env FILE\b0\fs24\par
\par
\b 3a. How environment variables load in the application\b0\par
\par
The application loads environment variables via this import at line 1 of server/index.ts:\par
\par
\pard\li720\f1\fs20\cf4 import \rquote dotenv/config\rquote ;\cf1\f0\fs24\par
\pard\par
The dotenv library (version 17.3.1) reads a .env file from the \b current working directory\b0  (process.cwd()) at import time. Critically, dotenv does NOT override environment variables that already exist in process.env.\par
\par
\b 3b. The PM2 working directory problem\b0\par
\par
The application on EC2 is managed by PM2. When PM2 starts the process, the current working directory depends on how PM2 was configured:\par
\par
\pard\li720 - If PM2 was started with "pm2 start" from /home/ubuntu/mattrmindrscribe, the CWD will be correct and dotenv will find the .env file.\par
 - If PM2 was started from a different directory, or if the PM2 ecosystem config specifies a different cwd, dotenv will look for .env in the WRONG directory and silently fail to load any variables from it.\par
 - If PM2 was originally started before AUPHONIC_API_KEY was added to .env, and the process has been "restarted" (not deleted and re-created), PM2 may cache the original environment.\par
\pard\par
The fact that OTHER environment variables work (DATABASE_URL, OPENAI_API_KEY, ANTHROPIC_API_KEY, etc.) does not necessarily prove dotenv is loading .env correctly. These variables may have been set in the PM2 ecosystem config, or exported in the shell profile (~/.bashrc, ~/.profile), or set via "pm2 set" or the PM2 environment. Only variables that exist EXCLUSIVELY in .env (like the newly added AUPHONIC_API_KEY) would reveal a dotenv loading failure.\par
\par
\b 3c. The critical evidence\b0\par
\par
AUPHONIC_API_KEY was added to the .env file AFTER the application was first deployed and PM2 was configured. All other API keys (OPENAI_API_KEY, ANTHROPIC_API_KEY, ASSEMBLYAI_API_KEY, etc.) were present in .env from the initial deployment. If PM2 cached the environment from the initial start, or if there is a separate mechanism loading those keys, the newly added AUPHONIC_API_KEY would not be picked up by a simple "pm2 restart."\par
\par
PM2\rquote s "restart" command reuses the saved environment by default. To force PM2 to re-read the environment, you would need to use "pm2 delete" followed by "pm2 start" (a full re-creation, not just a restart), or use the "--update-env" flag.\par
\par
Additionally, dotenv 17.x specifically states: "dotenv will never modify any environment variables that have already been set. If a variable already exists in process.env, dotenv will skip it." So if PM2 has a stale/empty AUPHONIC_API_KEY in its saved environment, dotenv will not overwrite it with the .env file value.\par
\par

\pard\f0\b\fs28 4. THE RELEVANT CODE PATH\b0\fs24\par
\par
The full chain from application startup to API failure:\par
\par
\b Step 1: Application starts, dotenv attempts to load .env\b0\par
\par
\pard\li720\f1\fs20\cf4 // server/index.ts, line 1\par
import \rquote dotenv/config\rquote ;\par
// dotenv reads process.cwd() + "/.env"\par
// If CWD is wrong, or .env doesn\rquote t exist there, nothing loads\par
// No error is thrown -- it silently continues\cf1\f0\fs24\par
\pard\par
\b Step 2: Transcript upload triggers the pipeline\b0\par
\par
\pard\li720\f1\fs20\cf4 // server/transcription.ts, lines 506-527\par
if (auphonicConfigured()) \{\par
  // This checks: !!process.env.AUPHONIC_API_KEY\par
  // Returns true if ANY value exists (even empty string is falsy)\par
  try \{\par
    pipelineLog.auphonic = \{ status: \rquote processing\rquote  \};\par
    const auphonicResult = await cleanAudioWithAuphonic(...);\par
  \} catch (err) \{\par
    // Error caught here, logged as non-fatal\par
    pipelineLog.auphonic = \{ status: \rquote error\rquote , error: err.message \};\par
  \}\par
\} else \{\par
  pipelineLog.auphonic = \{\par
    status: \rquote skipped\rquote ,\par
    reason: \rquote API key not configured\rquote\par
  \};\par
\}\cf1\f0\fs24\par
\pard\par
Important: since the error is "403" and not "skipped: API key not configured", we know that auphonicConfigured() returned true -- meaning SOME value exists in process.env.AUPHONIC_API_KEY. But that value may be wrong, corrupted, or stale.\par
\par
\b Step 3: The API call that fails\b0\par
\par
\pard\li720\f1\fs20\cf4 // server/auphonic.ts, lines 23-31\par
function getApiKey(): string \{\par
  const key = process.env.AUPHONIC_API_KEY;\par
  if (!key) throw new Error(\rquote AUPHONIC_API_KEY is not configured\rquote );\par
  return key;  // Returns whatever value is in the env var\par
\}\par
\par
function authHeader(): Record<string, string> \{\par
  return \{ Authorization: "Bearer " + getApiKey() \};\par
\}\par
\par
// server/auphonic.ts, lines 53-84\par
async function createProduction(title: string): Promise<string> \{\par
  const res = await fetch(\par
    "https://auphonic.com/api/productions.json",\par
    \{\par
      method: "POST",\par
      headers: \{\par
        ...authHeader(),\par
        "Content-Type": "application/json",\par
      \},\par
      body: JSON.stringify(\{ ... \}),\par
    \}\par
  );\par
\par
  if (!res.ok) \{\par
    const text = await res.text();\par
    throw new Error(\par
      "Auphonic create production failed (" + res.status + "): " + text\par
    );\par
    // ^^ THIS IS THE EXACT ERROR IN THE LOGS\par
  \}\par
