\pard\par

\pard\f0\b\fs28 5. SECOND AREA OF INVESTIGATION: fetch() AND THE Authorization HEADER\b0\fs24\par
\par
\b 5a. Node.js fetch() behavior with Authorization headers\b0\par
\par
The application uses Node.js\rquote s built-in fetch() API (available since Node 18). There is a known behavior in Node.js\rquote s undici-based fetch implementation: when a request encounters a redirect (3xx), fetch() \b strips the Authorization header\b0  from the redirected request for security reasons.\par
\par
If Auphonic\rquote s /api/productions.json endpoint redirects (e.g., from HTTP to HTTPS, or from one subdomain to another), the Authorization header would be silently removed from the follow-up request. The final request would arrive at Auphonic without any authentication, resulting in exactly the error we see: "Token doesn\rquote t exist."\par
\par
This behavior is specific to Node.js\rquote s fetch(). The reference implementation uses axios, which preserves Authorization headers across redirects by default. This could explain why:\par
\par
\pard\li720 - The same key works from Replit (different network path, possibly no redirect)\par
 - The same key fails from EC2 (different network path, possibly triggers a redirect)\par
 - The /api/user.json test from Replit worked (GET request, may not redirect)\par
 - The /api/productions.json POST from EC2 fails (POST may redirect differently)\par
\pard\par
\b 5b. Evidence for this hypothesis\b0\par
\par
The reference implementation (auphonic-service.js) uses axios with maxRedirects: 5 set explicitly. Axios preserves auth headers across redirects. Our implementation uses Node.js fetch() which does NOT preserve auth headers across redirects. If the Auphonic API issues any redirect on the production creation endpoint, this would silently strip our credentials.\par
\par
This is especially relevant because the reference code was clearly written by someone who had working knowledge of the Auphonic API. Their explicit use of axios with maxRedirects may not be coincidental -- it may be specifically because they encountered redirect-related auth issues with other HTTP clients.\par
\par

\pard\f0\b\fs28 6. THIRD AREA: THE .env FILE STATE ON EC2\b0\fs24\par
\par
Even after editing the .env file to contain the correct key and removing duplicates, several issues could persist:\par
\par
\pard\li360\b 6a. Invisible characters in the key value\b0\par
\pard\li720 If the .env file was edited on Windows or with certain editors, carriage return characters (\\r) may be present at the end of the line. The key would be loaded as "CaN3...\\r" instead of "CaN3..." -- the trailing \\r becomes part of the Bearer token sent to Auphonic, which would not match any token in their system. This can be checked with: cat -A /home/ubuntu/mattrmindrscribe/.env | grep AUPHONIC  (\\r characters appear as ^M).\par
\par
\pard\li360\b 6b. Quoting issues\b0\par
\pard\li720 dotenv handles quotes differently depending on the version. In dotenv 17.x, if the value is wrapped in single or double quotes in the .env file, the quotes are stripped. But if only one quote is present (unmatched), the quote character becomes part of the value. For example: AUPHONIC_API_KEY=\rquote CaN3...\rquote  would work (quotes stripped), but AUPHONIC_API_KEY=\rquote CaN3... (missing closing quote) would include the opening quote in the value.\par
\par
\pard\li360\b 6c. PM2 environment caching\b0\par
\pard\li720 As discussed in section 3, PM2 caches the process environment. Using "pm2 restart" does not re-read the .env file. The --update-env flag was shown in the deployment screenshots (the yellow warning message), but this flag only updates PM2\rquote s own environment variables (set via pm2 set), not the ones loaded by dotenv at runtime. The definitive way to force a clean environment is: pm2 delete mattrmindrscribe, then re-start the process from the correct working directory.\par
\pard\par

\pard\f0\b\fs28 7. DIAGNOSTIC COMMANDS\b0\fs24\par
\par
The following commands would definitively identify which cause is at play:\par
\par
\b Verify the exact key value PM2 is passing to the process:\b0\par
\pard\li720\f1\fs20 pm2 env 0 | grep AUPHONIC\f0\fs24\par
\pard\par
\b Test the key directly from EC2 via curl:\b0\par
\pard\li720\f1\fs20 source /home/ubuntu/mattrmindrscribe/.env && \\\par
curl -s -H "Authorization: Bearer $AUPHONIC_API_KEY" \\\par
  https://auphonic.com/api/user.json\f0\fs24\par
\pard\par
\b Check for invisible characters in the .env file:\b0\par
\pard\li720\f1\fs20 cat -A /home/ubuntu/mattrmindrscribe/.env | grep AUPHONIC\f0\fs24\par
\pard\par
\b Check for redirects on the Auphonic API endpoint:\b0\par
\pard\li720\f1\fs20 source /home/ubuntu/mattrmindrscribe/.env && \\\par
curl -v -X POST \\\par
  -H "Authorization: Bearer $AUPHONIC_API_KEY" \\\par
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \\\par
  -d \rquote \{"metadata":\{"title":"test"\}\}\rquote  \\\par
  https://auphonic.com/api/productions.json 2>&1 | head -40\f0\fs24\par
\pard\par
\b Force a completely clean PM2 restart:\b0\par
\pard\li720\f1\fs20 cd /home/ubuntu/mattrmindrscribe && \\\par
pm2 delete mattrmindrscribe && \\\par
pm2 start npm --name mattrmindrscribe -- start\f0\fs24\par
\pard\par

\pard\f0\b\fs28 8. SUMMARY\b0\fs24\par
\par
After exhausting the obvious causes (wrong auth scheme, wrong API key, duplicate entries), two primary areas remain:\par
\par
\pard\li360\b 1. PM2 environment caching / dotenv not loading the key.\b0  The AUPHONIC_API_KEY was added after initial deployment. PM2 "restart" does not re-read .env files. The process may be running with a stale or empty value for this variable. A full PM2 delete + restart from the correct directory would resolve this.\par
\par
\b 2. Node.js fetch() stripping the Authorization header on redirect.\b0  If Auphonic\rquote s API redirects the POST request, Node\rquote s fetch() silently removes the Authorization header. The reference implementation uses axios specifically (with maxRedirects: 5), which preserves auth headers across redirects. This would explain why the same key works from Replit but fails from EC2 -- different network paths may trigger different redirect behavior.\par
\pard\par
The diagnostic commands in Section 7 will definitively identify which of these causes is responsible. Running them in order will isolate whether the key is reaching the process correctly (PM2 issue) or whether the HTTP request itself is losing the credentials (fetch/redirect issue).\par
}